Major differences in major championship venues


In August 2021, the USGA revealed the organization’s latest set of future sites for its top championships. Senior managing director of championships John Bodenhamer had this to say about a set of courses that included heavy hitters like Merion and Oakmont:

“We’ve asked players where they want to win their U.S. Open and we know the sites they speak of very highly. The ghosts of the past matter. What has come before these great players … Hogan in 1953 at Oakmont, Nicklaus and Palmer [in 1962], DJ in 2016. All the great moments that are here, that matters. When a man or woman wins, I won where this happened, that’s hugely important.”

One of the marks of a major championship is the prestige of the venue where it is held. The Masters earns the highest television ratings and is the tournament pros most want to win not because of its field, which is the weakest of the four majors. It’s all about the history of Bobby Jones and Augusta National.

Unlike the Masters, USGA tournaments travel around the country to different host sites. The six most important USGA events are aimed at the world’s best professional and amateur players - the U.S. Open (founded in 1895), U.S. Amateur (1895), and Walker Cup (1922) on the men’s side, and the U.S. Women’s Open (1946), U.S. Women’s Amateur (1895), and Curtis Cup (1932) on the women’s side.

All of these competitions have decades of history and the imprimatur of the country’s top golf organization. Bodenhamer is right to point out that both male and female players value winning at the most historic venues. But has the USGA given them the opportunity to do so?

The following analysis is based on three data sets: a list of major host sites and the Golf Digest and Golf Magazine rankings of the best courses in America since 1985 (when Golf Digest began using the 1-100 rankings; Golf Magazine followed suit in 1991). For each pairing of year and course, we take the highest ranking a course received in one of the two publications within five years of hosting the tournament. As an example, Olympic Club’s Lake course hosted the US Open in 2012. In the four rankings between 2009 and 2015, Golf Digest rated it 26th, 27th, 26th, and 35th, while Golf Magazine rated it 25th, 25th, 30th, and 33rd. We take the most generous rating and mark down Olympic at 25th for the 2012 US Open.

Let’s start with the men’s events, showing year on the x-axis (left is earlier, right is later) and ranking on the y-axis (better rankings are at the top, while lower rankings are at the bottom). Dots appearing in the shaded red area at the bottom were unranked in both lists at the time of the event.

  • US Opens are almost exclusively played at the nation’s top-ranked courses. Every single US Open has been played at a ranked course, and the vast majority of events since 1983 have been hosted by a course ranked in the top 30 at the time by Golf Digest or Golf Magazine.

  • There is a clear recent trend of the US Open visiting some less heralded venues. Mike Davis’s tenure as head of the USGA was highlighted by the decision to host US Opens at nontraditional public courses. As a result, the average ranking slipped substantially in the mid-2000s. Torrey Pines, host of the 2008 and 2021 events, is the least-regarded course to host a US Open in the past 30 years, and perhaps ever. Bodenhamer’s recent “don’t call it a rota” rota announcement may mark the end of this experiment.

  • Walker Cup venues match US Opens in prestige and may even overshadow them in exclusivity. The Walker Cup, hosted quadrenially in the US, is catnip for some of the country’s most exclusive clubs. (The word “club” can be used instead of “course” - Walker Cup has never been played at a single American public venue in its 100-year history.) Pine Valley, National Golf Links of America, Peachtree, and Seminole may not have the viewing space, course length, or member willingness to host a major stroke play event where the organizers will mandate course changes in order to protect par, but they are happy to host a match play tournament for 24 top amateurs and a few hundred spectators.

  • The US Amateur is a notch below the US Open and Walker Cup but still played almost exclusively at ranked courses. The US Am is a large-scale event requiring two courses and six days of competition to identify a winner among over 300 competitors. As a result, most venues have multiple courses on the premises and those that don’t tend to be in major metropolitan areas with another top-level course nearby. There is a decent amount of overlap between US Open and US Amateur venues at the top levels with the exception of Shinnecock Hills, which hasn’t hosted a US Am since the second playing of the event in 1896.

Now for the women’s tournaments:

  • US Women’s Opens are typically, but not always, hosted at ranked courses. US Women’s Open venues are hardly terrible - most are ranked in the top 100. But unlike the men’s Open, top 20 courses are rare and more than a third of US Womens Opens since 1983 were played at unranked courses. Classic US Open hosts like Shinnecock Hills, Merion, Winged Foot, and Pebble Beach are nowhere to be found.

  • The Curtis Cup vs. Walker Cup comparison is similar. Curtis Cup venues are by no means weak, with three of the four clubs that were unranked at the time of the event since popping back in the top 100. But again, they do not have the ranking or prestige of Walker Cup courses like Pine Valley or National.

  • US Women’s Amateur venues clearly lag behind the US Am. This is the most obvious area of inequality, bordering on scandalous. So many US Women’s Amateurs were hosted at unranked venues that the text labels don’t even fit on the chart. Since 2009, the US Women’s Amateur hasn’t been played at a single course ranked in the top 100; since 2001, it hasn’t been played at a single course ranked in the top 50.

Men vs. women fast facts:

  • Only two top 10 courses (Oakmont and Pinehurst) have ever hosted the US Women’s Open. By contrast, more than half of US Opens have been held at top 10 courses.
  • Only three top 10 courses have ever hosted the US Women’s Amateur, and none since 1995. By contrast, three of the four most recent US Amateurs were held at top 10 courses.
  • The US Women’s Amateur hasn’t played at a ranked course of any kind since 2008. By contrast, the US Amateur’s only visit to an unranked course since 1995 was the Atlanta Athletic Club, which has hosted a US Open and three PGA Championships.
  • No top 25 course has ever hosted the Curtis Cup, while all but two Walker Cups were hosted at top 25 courses.
  • So many unranked courses have hosted the US Women’s Open and US Women’s Amateur that the text labels don’t even fit on the charts.
